### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/releated to the feature request?

router

### Description

Rendering an app in SSR (using nguniversal) with an invalid URL (e.g. http://localhost:4200/electronics-spa/en/USD/Brands/Canon/c/brand_10%20or%20(1,2)=(select*from(select%20name_const(CHAR(82,88,106,99,113,78,74,70,73,118,87),1),name_const(CHAR(82,88,106,99,113,78,74,70,73,118,87),1))a)%20--%20and%201%3D1) causes the render to hang, and never release the taken resources.

The reason is that the navigation never completes on error, when the `Router` option `initialNavigation` is set to `enabled`.

### Proposed solution

Expose `RouterInitializer`.

### Alternatives considered

We came up with this _workaround_, but it would be nice if `…µangular_packages_router_router_h` could be exposed.

```ts
import { Injectable, Injector, Provider } from '@angular/core';
import {
  NavigationError,
  Router,
  ROUTER_CONFIGURATION,
  …µangular_packages_router_router_h as RouterInitializer,
} from '@angular/router';
import { filter, take } from 'rxjs/operators';

@Injectable()
export class CustomRouterInitializer extends RouterInitializer {
  appInitializer(): Promise<any> {
    const injector: Injector = (this as any).injector;
    const opts = injector.get(ROUTER_CONFIGURATION);

    if (
      opts.initialNavigation ===
      'enabled' /* for Ng11: || opts.initialNavigation === 'enabledBlocking' */
    ) {
      let resolve: any;
      const res = new Promise((r) => (resolve = r));

      injector
        .get(Router)
        .events.pipe(
          // We want to explicitly react on NavigationError event occurs just
          // after the first navigation start event
          take(2),
          filter((event) => event instanceof NavigationError)
        )
        .subscribe(() => resolve(false));

      super.appInitializer().then((val) => resolve(val));
      return res;
    }

    return super.appInitializer();
  }
}

export const routerFixProvider: Provider = {
  provide: RouterInitializer,
  useClass: CustomRouterInitializer,
};
```

The above workaround is for ng12. 
I noticed that in ng13 there's no similar private API available, unless I'm missing something.

### What are you trying to do?

I have built a custom Web Application theme based on Angular Material UI Components. I'm overriding styles using @mixins and it was working in previous version of Angular/Angular Material (7 and up to 9). The problem occured after upgrading from Angular 9 to Angular 12. 

This how my styles.scss looks like:

``` scss
@use "~@angular/material" as mat;
 @include mat.core();

// Themes
@import "./themes/default-theme.scss";
@import "./themes/dark-theme.scss";

// Colors
@import "./scss/colors.scss";

// Main Mixin
@mixin custom-components-theme($theme, $colors) {
  @include app-style-theme($theme, $colors);
  @include secondary-sidenav-theme($theme, $colors);
  @include yes-no-theme($theme, $colors);
  @include skeleton-loader-theme($theme, $colors);
  @include avatar-bar-theme($theme, $colors);
  @include bottom-nav-theme($theme, $colors);
}

@include mat.all-component-themes($actulite-light-theme);

.default-theme {
  @include custom-components-theme(
    $actulite-light-theme,
    $colors-default-theme
  );
}

.black-theme {
  @include custom-components-theme($actualite-dark-theme, $colors-dark-theme);
}
```


### What troubleshooting steps have you tried?

- I was suspecting that Angular Material didn't load properly but it is working perfectly fine.
- The mixin override works on Angular 9 (Last stable version of the project).

### Reproduction

Steps to reproduce:
1. Load Angular Material theme.
2. Override Styles using mixins.


### Environment

- Angular: 12.2.13
- CDK/Material: 12.2.13
- Browser(s): Goggle Chrome
- Operating System (e.g. Windows, macOS, Ubuntu): Windows, Ubuntu (Using Docker containers)

